---
import Layout from '../layouts/layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Transplant Plan — Perennial Bed">
  <div class="animate-in space-y-10">
    <div>
      <h1 class="text-5xl font-semibold text-ink tracking-tight">Transplant plan</h1>
      <p class="text-ink-soft mt-3 text-lg">
        Moving perennials from the crowded metal bed to the freshly composted bed — April 2026.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="bg-emerald-50/70 border border-emerald-200 rounded-xl p-5">
      <p class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-emerald-800">Done (April 15-16)</p>
      <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1.5 text-ink-soft">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Gave all citrus a handful of fruit fertiliser each (April 15)</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Cleared all 3 raised beds of dead tomatoes/basil</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Worked compost into cleared beds</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Transplanted surviving Echinacea clump into the new bed</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Divided Achillea, spread across both beds</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Watered in the new bed deeply</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-emerald-700">✓</span>Epsom salts drench on all citrus (April 16)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="bg-terra-soft/60 border border-terra/20 rounded-xl p-5">
      <p class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-terra">Next — do now / this week</p>
      <ul class="mt-2 space-y-1.5 text-ink-soft">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">1.</span><span><strong class="text-ink">Mulch the new bed</strong> — 3-5cm sugar cane or pea straw, keep 5cm off stems/crowns</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">2.</span><span><strong class="text-ink">Watch for wilting</strong> over 1-2 weeks (normal transplant shock). Water gently if leaves look sad.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">3.</span><span><strong class="text-ink">No fertiliser for 2-3 weeks</strong> on the transplants. Let roots establish first.</span></li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">4.</span><span><strong class="text-ink">Follow-up Epsom salts</strong> in 2-3 weeks if the citrus leaves are still showing yellowing</span></li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
      <p class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink">What the result looks like</p>
      <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1">Below: the original bed (now mostly Rudbeckia) and the new bed with the transplanted clumps.</p>
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mt-4">
        <figure class="annotated">
          <img src="/images/plants/IMG_1017.jpg" alt="Original bed after transplant" />
          <span class="annot leave" style="top: 50%; left: 0%; width: 30%; height: 45%;">
            <em>STAY</em> Rudbeckia
          </span>
        </figure>
        <figure class="annotated">
          <img src="/images/plants/IMG_1018.jpg" alt="New bed with transplants" />
          <span class="annot move" style="top: 30%; left: 15%; width: 30%; height: 50%;">
            <em>NEW</em> Echinacea
          </span>
          <span class="annot move" style="top: 30%; left: 60%; width: 30%; height: 50%;">
            <em>NEW</em> Achillea
          </span>
        </figure>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="border-rule-light" />

    <section class="bg-olive-soft/60 border border-olive/10 rounded-xl p-5">
      <p class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-olive">Reference: Why April was right</p>
      <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1">
        April in Melbourne is ideal — soil still warm enough for roots to establish, cool air reduces transplant shock, plants are slowing down so energy goes into roots instead of top growth.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-ink">The perennial bed — what's what</h2>
      <p class="text-ink-soft">Annotated view of the messy end of the bed. Colour-coded: green = move, amber = leave, grey = unsure.</p>

      <figure class="annotated">
        <img src="/images/plants/IMG_1011.jpg" alt="Perennial bed annotated" />
        <span class="annot move" style="top: 8%; left: 45%; width: 50%; height: 55%;">
          <em>MOVE</em> Achillea — divide
        </span>
        <span class="annot move" style="top: 55%; left: 25%; width: 30%; height: 30%;">
          <em>MOVE</em> Echinacea
        </span>
        <span class="annot leave" style="top: 60%; left: 0%; width: 24%; height: 38%;">
          <em>LEAVE</em> Rudbeckia
        </span>
      </figure>

      <figure class="annotated">
        <img src="/images/plants/IMG_1008.jpg" alt="Perennial bed top-down annotated" />
        <span class="annot move" style="top: 20%; left: 25%; width: 45%; height: 55%;">
          <em>MOVE</em> Echinacea rosette
        </span>
        <span class="annot move" style="top: 10%; left: 65%; width: 28%; height: 35%;">
          <em>MOVE</em> Achillea
        </span>
      </figure>

      <figure class="annotated">
        <img src="/images/plants/IMG_1009.jpg" alt="Cut-back Achillea flowering stem" />
        <span class="annot move" style="top: 5%; left: 30%; width: 60%; height: 50%;">
          <em>MOVE</em> Achillea flowering stem — toppled when tall, cut back. This is the same plant as the ferny foliage on the right of the bed. More of it than it looked.
        </span>
      </figure>

      <div class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
        <p class="font-display text-lg font-semibold text-ink mb-2">Identifying the plants</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2.5 text-ink-soft">
          <li><span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-emerald-500 mr-2 align-middle"></span><span class="text-ink font-medium">Echinacea</span> — larger coarse dark-green leaves, red flower plus multiple emerging green buds. Clumping basal rosette.</li>
          <li><span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-emerald-500 mr-2 align-middle"></span><span class="text-ink font-medium">Achillea (Yarrow)</span> — fine ferny grey-green foliage. Very distinctive. Lots of it on the right side.</li>
          <li><span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-amber-500 mr-2 align-middle"></span><span class="text-ink font-medium">Rudbeckia</span> — yellow daisy flowers, broad dark green leaves, dominating the bed.</li>
          <li><span class="inline-block w-3 h-3 rounded-full bg-stone-400 mr-2 align-middle"></span><span class="text-ink font-medium">Salvia nemorosa</span> — was cut back hard, probably dormant. Watch for basal rosette of green leaves emerging in spring.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-ink">The destination — cleared veggie bed</h2>
      <figure class="annotated">
        <img src="/images/plants/IMG_0993.jpg" alt="Cleared and composted veggie bed" />
        <span class="annot destination" style="top: 5%; left: 5%; width: 90%; height: 90%;">
          <em>NEW HOME</em> Fresh compost, no competitors
        </span>
      </figure>
      <p class="text-ink-soft">Cleared and composted April 16. Fresh soil, no competing roots, better drainage than the other bed (once Echinacea is out of the overwatered environment it should really take off).</p>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-ink">Step-by-step</h2>
      <ol class="space-y-4 list-decimal list-inside">
        <li class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
          <span class="font-medium text-ink">Water the source plants</span>
          <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1 ml-5">The night before. Makes digging cleaner and reduces root damage.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
          <span class="font-medium text-ink">Dig the Achillea first</span>
          <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1 ml-5">Dig wide around the clump, lift with as much root as possible. Split into 2-3 divisions with a spade. Replant some in the new bed, keep some in the old bed (spread them out from the Rudbeckia).</p>
        </li>
        <li class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
          <span class="font-medium text-ink">Dig the Echinacea</span>
          <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1 ml-5">The one with flowers and emerging buds. Take the whole clump — don't divide it, it's not robust enough yet. Replant at the same depth in the new bed.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
          <span class="font-medium text-ink">Water in, then mulch</span>
          <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1 ml-5">Thorough soak on everything. Then mulch the new bed — keep mulch off the stems/crowns. 5cm is plenty.</p>
        </li>
        <li class="bg-paper rounded-xl border border-rule-light p-5">
          <span class="font-medium text-ink">Don't overwater through winter</span>
          <p class="text-ink-soft mt-1 ml-5">This is what killed the Echinacea originally. Rain should be enough. Only water if there's a dry spell or the leaves wilt.</p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="space-y-4">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-ink">Optional — fill the gaps</h2>
      <p class="text-ink-soft">The new bed will have room for 2-3 more plants alongside the transplants. Good companions that handle metal-bed conditions:</p>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-ink-soft">
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">·</span>More Salvia varieties (S. nemorosa, S. greggii, S. 'Love and Wishes')</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">·</span>Catmint (Nepeta 'Walker's Low') — purple flowers, grey-green foliage</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">·</span>Russian sage (Perovskia) — similar palette, very drought-tolerant</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">·</span>Another Achillea cultivar (different colour) — yarrow are bulletproof</li>
        <li class="flex gap-3"><span class="text-terra">·</span>Sedum 'Autumn Joy' — late colour, tough as nails</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  .annotated {
    position: relative;
    display: block;
    border-radius: 12px;
    overflow: hidden;
    border: 1px solid var(--color-rule-light);
  }
  .annotated img {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }
  .annot {
    position: absolute;
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    justify-content: flex-start;
    padding: 8px 10px;
    font-size: 13px;
    font-weight: 600;
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 2px rgba(255,255,255,0.35) inset;
  }
  .annot em {
    font-style: normal;
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    font-size: 11px;
    margin-right: 6px;
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    background: rgba(255,255,255,0.9);
  }
  .annot.move {
    border: 3px solid #10b981;
    background: rgba(16, 185, 129, 0.12);
    color: #065f46;
  }
  .annot.move em { color: #065f46; }
  .annot.leave {
    border: 3px solid #f59e0b;
    background: rgba(245, 158, 11, 0.12);
    color: #78350f;
  }
  .annot.leave em { color: #78350f; }
  .annot.unsure {
    border: 3px dashed #78716c;
    background: rgba(120, 113, 108, 0.1);
    color: #44403c;
  }
  .annot.unsure em { color: #44403c; }
  .annot.destination {
    border: 3px solid var(--color-terra);
    background: rgba(196, 97, 58, 0.1);
    color: var(--color-terra);
    align-items: flex-start;
    justify-content: center;
    padding-top: 16px;
  }
  .annot.destination em {
    color: var(--color-terra);
  }
</style>
